== NzbDAV Frontend Architecture Rules ==

**Core Technology Stack**

Framework & Tools

- React Router v7 with SSR enabled - Full-stack React framework with server-side rendering
- TypeScript - All code must be written in TypeScript, prefer interfaces over types
- Vite - Build tool and dev server
- Express.js - Backend proxy server
- Bootstrap + React-Bootstrap - Primary UI framework (NOT Tailwind despite .cursorrules)
- CSS Modules - Scoped styling system

**File Structure & Organization**

Directory Naming

- Use lowercase with dashes for directories: queue-table/, left-navigation/
- Component directories follow pattern: component-name/component-name.tsx

Component Structure

component-name/
├── component-name.tsx # Main component
├── component-name.module.css # Scoped styles
└── component-name.module.css.d.ts # TypeScript definitions for CSS

Route Structure

routes/
├── \_index/ # Home page layout with shared components
├── queue/ # Queue & History page
├── settings/ # Settings with nested tabs
├── explore/ # File browser
└── integrity-results/ # Integrity check results

Styling Rules

- CSS Modules Pattern
- Every component gets its own .module.css file
- Import styles as: import styles from "./component.module.css"
- Use className={styles.className} in JSX
- Generate TypeScript definitions: .module.css.d.ts files
- Bootstrap Integration
- Use React-Bootstrap components: Button, Form, Alert, Card, etc.
- Import from react-bootstrap: import { Button, Form } from 'react-bootstrap'
- Global Bootstrap CSS imported in root.tsx
- CSS Class Naming
- Use kebab-case in CSS: .queue-icon, .left-navigation
- Access in TypeScript: styles["queue-icon"], styles.leftNavigation

**React Patterns**

Component Architecture

- Functional components only - No class components
- Use named exports: export function ComponentName() {}
- Structure: exported component → subcomponents → helpers → types

TypeScript Integration

- Use interfaces for props: interface ComponentProps {}
- Route components get: type Route.LoaderArgs and type Route.ActionArgs
- Prefer interface over type declarations

State Management

- Use React hooks: useState, useEffect, useCallback
- No external state management (Redux/Zustand)
- Pass props down through component tree

**Routing & Data Loading**

Route Structure

- File-based routing: routes/page-name/route.tsx
- Each route exports: loader(), action(), and default component
- Use useLoaderData() to access server data

Server-Side Data Fetching
export async function loader({ request }: Route.LoaderArgs) {
// Fetch data on server before rendering
const data = await backendClient.getSomeData();
return { data };
}

Authentication Flow

- All routes protected except /login and /onboarding
- Authentication check in root.tsx loader
- Redirect to /login if not authenticated
- Session storage handles auth state

**Backend Integration**

Proxy Architecture

- Frontend server proxies API/WebDAV requests to backend
- Backend URL: process.env.BACKEND_URL
- Automatic API key injection for authenticated requests

API Communication

- Use frontend proxy instead of direct backend calls
- Routes: /api/\* → proxied to backend
- Authentication handled automatically by proxy

Backend Client

- Centralized client: ~/clients/backend-client.server.ts
- Server-side only (.server.ts suffix)
- Handles API communication patterns

**Real-Time Updates**

WebSocket Architecture

- Centralized WebSocket server: server/websocket.server.ts
- Topics-based subscriptions: Subscribe to specific topics
- Automatic reconnection and authentication

WebSocket Usage Pattern

// Subscribe to topics
const topicSubscriptions = {
'topic-name': 'state', // or 'event'
};

// Handle messages
useEffect(() => {
const ws = new WebSocket(window.location.origin.replace(/^http/, 'ws'));
ws.onmessage = receiveMessage((topic, message) => {
// Handle real-time updates
});
ws.onopen = () => ws.send(JSON.stringify(topicSubscriptions));
}, []);

Message Types

- State topics: Get current state + updates
- Event topics: Only receive new events
- Use receiveMessage() utility for parsing

**Code Style Rules**

Function Declarations

- Use function keyword for pure functions: function ComponentName() {}
- Use arrow functions for event handlers: const handleClick = () => {}

Naming Conventions

- Components: PascalCase - LeftNavigation
- Files: kebab-case - left-navigation.tsx
- Variables: camelCase with auxiliary verbs - isLoading, hasError
- CSS classes: kebab-case - .left-navigation

Import Organization

- React/Router imports first
- External libraries
- Internal utilities (~/utils/, ~/clients/)
- Relative imports (./component)
- CSS imports last

**Development Patterns**

Environment Configuration

- Development: npm run dev (port 5173)
- Build: npm run build (creates build/ directory)
- TypeScript: npm run typecheck

Server Integration

- Frontend server handles SSR + proxying
- WebSocket server integrated into Express app
- Development: Hot reload with Vite
- Production: Built assets served by Express

Error Handling

- Server errors: Return error objects from loaders
- Client errors: Use React error boundaries
- Network errors: Handle in try/catch blocks

**Performance Rules**

Optimization Strategies

- Server-side rendering for initial page load
- Component-level CSS modules for styling isolation
- Efficient WebSocket subscriptions (only needed topics)
- Immutable data patterns for state updates

Bundle Optimization

- Route-based code splitting automatic with React Router
- CSS modules prevent style conflicts
- Tree shaking with ES modules

**Conditional Features**

Feature Flags

- Check feature availability in root.tsx loader
- Pass flags as props to navigation components
- Example: integrityEnabled controls integrity results nav item

Dynamic Navigation

- Navigation items can be conditionally rendered
- Based on backend configuration or user permissions
- Example: Integrity Results only shows if integrity checking enabled

**Deployment Considerations**

Build Process

- Client bundle: Static assets for browser
- Server bundle: SSR-enabled Express app
- Asset optimization: Automatic with Vite

Environment Variables

- BACKEND_URL: Backend service location
- FRONTEND_BACKEND_API_KEY: Authentication key
- NODE_ENV: Development/production mode
